lyses call for a vital and unprecedented process of listening to the stories that Indigenous peoples have been telling about this continent for centuries. At the same time, she performs this process herself, creating a model for listening and for incorporating those stories throughout. This commitment to listening is analogous to homing – the sophisticated skill that turtles, insects, lobsters, birds, and countless other beings use to return to sites of familiarity. Bryant adopts the homing process as a reading strategy that continuously seeks to transcend the distortions and distractions that were intentionally built into Settler Canadian culture across centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturexIndian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aColonization in literature. 0aIndians in literature. 0aPioneers in literature. 4aHistory. 4aIndigenous Studies. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh  a.  aAmerican studies.  aCanadian studies.  aIndigenous literacies.  aIndigenous studies.  aatlantic world.  aborder studies.  acolonial northeast.  aeastern Canada.  ahemispheric studies.  aliterary history.  anon-alphabetic literature.  anortheastern North America.  areconciliation.  asettler colonial studies.  atransatlantic.  awhat is an early American.  awhat is literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112288740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771122887423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771122887/original  a978-3-11-127